<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="70" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,318,558]" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,267,427,449]" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">Diagnosis:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[267,531,428,449]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Cyatheaceae" genus="Sphaeropteris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cyatheales" pageId="1" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="guangxiensis">
<emphasis box="[267,531,428,449]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">Sphaeropteris guangxiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[709,833,428,449]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Cyatheaceae" genus="Sphaeropteris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cyatheales" pageId="1" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brunonina">
<emphasis box="[709,833,428,449]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">S. brunonina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. M. Tryon" authorityYear="1970" baseAuthorityName="Ching" baseAuthorityYear="1959" box="[880,1019,428,449]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Cyatheaceae" genus="Sphaeropteris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cyatheales" pageId="1" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis box="[880,1019,428,449]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">S. hainanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in terms of morphological characters of leaf, but the difference is that fiddleheads (young leaves spirally coiled in bud) of 
<taxonomicName box="[921,1069,464,485]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Cyatheaceae" genus="Sphaeropteris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cyatheales" pageId="1" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="guangxiensis">
<emphasis box="[921,1069,464,485]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">S. guangxiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are densely scaly on the adaxial surface and few on the abaxial surface, fiddleheads of 
<taxonomicName box="[640,765,500,521]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Cyatheaceae" genus="Sphaeropteris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cyatheales" pageId="1" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brunonina">
<emphasis box="[640,765,500,521]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">S. brunonina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are fully scaly on both sides, and fiddleheads of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. M. Tryon" authorityYear="1970" baseAuthorityName="Ching" baseAuthorityYear="1959" box="[1239,1379,500,521]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Cyatheaceae" genus="Sphaeropteris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cyatheales" pageId="1" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis box="[1239,1379,500,521]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">S. hainanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not scaly (
<figureCitation box="[251,358,536,558]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[136,229,949,971]" captionTargetBox="[164,1429,198,916]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[151,1436,190,924]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Fiddleheads and sori on pinnule segments.—A &amp; D. Sphaeropteris brunoniana.—B &amp; E. S. guangxiensis.—C &amp; F. S. hainanensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5448021" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5448021/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="70">Figure 3 A</figureCitation>
~C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
